<td>Bio</td>
<td>co-founder &amp; cto | <span class="citation"
data-cites="octra-labs">@octra-labs</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Location</td>
<td>London.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>Fifteen minutes after the GitHub account creation, at 14:15:45 UTC,
the GitHub organisation <a
href="https://github.com/octra-labs">octra-labs</a> was created,
describing itself as a “non-profit association of researchers and
builders who develop fast and reliable FHE solutions for blockchain, AI
and ML.” The organisation had verifiable control over
<code>octra.org</code>. The domain, developer account, and organisation
were all created in a single fifty-seven minute window. In the three and
a half years following this fifty-seven minute window, the project
claimed to raise <a
href="https://xcancel.com/octra/status/1837084359255314940">$4 million
in pre-seed funding</a> and sell <a href="https://archive.ph/mcaEt">$20
million in tokens at a $200 million valuation</a>. The point to be made
here is more that “Octra” was a name created out of thin air. There were
no EUROCRYPT showings of this technology, there was no IACR papers
preceding its creation, and the developer, as we know so far, is
pseudonymous. This is important, as big technology such as this rarely
comes out of nowhere with little backing on its own (even <a
href="https://bitcoin.org/bitcoin.pdf">Bitcoin released as a
whitepaper</a>).</p>
<h4 id="a-house-of-cards">A House of Cards</h4>
<p>So what is fully-homomorphic about HFHE? Mayhaps we will ask the
whitepaper? Unfortunately, there isn’t one. Only the <a
href="https://octra.org/litepaper.pdf">litepaper</a> and the <a
href="https://docs.octra.org">docs</a> (This is before addressing the
codebases). But let’s be fair for giggles. HFHE is <a
href="https://docs.octra.org/tech-docs/hfhe#:~:text=HFHE%20(Hypergraph%20Fully%20Homomorphic%20Encryption)%20is%20an%20approach%20to%20implementing%20a%20bootstrap%20FHE%20scheme%20using%20hypergraphs.">described</a>
by the docs as an approach to a bootstrap FHE scheme using hypergraphs
(in that it treats activity and inactivity as the bits and uses unions
and intersections to build its binary operations). On the page hosting
that description, it claims that “the implementation of logical gates
through hypergraphs enables efficient binary operations.” We don’t have
issues with this claim. After it defines the logical binary operations,
it goes on to state the following:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>these hypergraph-based implementations provide an approach to solving
full homomorphic encryption problems.</p>
<p>hypergraphs naturally support parallel computation because different
nodes and hyperedges are processed independently.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>To say there exists a gap in literature regarding the efficiency of
logic-gate with hypergraphs transferring to efficiency in FHE would be a
cruel understatement to how sparsely this has been researched. It is
important to note that such does not constitute falsehood. Many of <a
href="https://wikipedia.org/wiki/CryptoNote">Saberhagen</a>’s concepts
were relatively novel, unformulated until that point. We will see why
Octra does not reflect The docs themselves are incredibly lacking.
Encryption, decryption, and addition are standard <a
href="https://wikipedia.org/wiki/Paillier_cryptosystem">Paillier</a>, a
cryptosystem which is additive only.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb1"><pre
class="sourceCode ocaml"><code class="sourceCode ocaml"><span id="cb1-1"><a href="#cb1-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">(* encryption *)</span></span>
<span id="cb1-2"><a href="#cb1-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="kw">let</span> encrypt m (n, g) =</span>
<span id="cb1-3"><a href="#cb1-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="kw">let</span> lower = Z.one <span class="kw">in</span></span>
<span id="cb1-4"><a href="#cb1-4" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="kw">let</span> upper = Z.<span class="dt">pred</span> n <span class="kw">in</span></span>
<span id="cb1-5"><a href="#cb1-5" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="kw">let</span> diff = Z.sub upper lower <span class="kw">in</span></span>
<span id="cb1-6"><a href="#cb1-6" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="kw">let</span> gm = Z.powm g m (Z.mul n n) <span class="kw">in</span></span>
<span id="cb1-7"><a href="#cb1-7" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="kw">let</span> rn = Z.powm r n (Z.mul n n) <span class="kw">in</span></span>
<span id="cb1-8"><a href="#cb1-8" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  Z.rem (Z.mul gm rn) (Z.mul n n)</span>
<span id="cb1-9"><a href="#cb1-9" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  </span>
<span id="cb1-10"><a href="#cb1-10" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">(* ... *)</span></span>
<span id="cb1-11"><a href="#cb1-11" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb1-12"><a href="#cb1-12" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">(* decryption *)</span></span>
<span id="cb1-13"><a href="#cb1-13" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="kw">let</span> decrypt c (n, _) (lambda, mu) =</span>
<span id="cb1-14"><a href="#cb1-14" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="kw">let</span> cl = Z.powm c lambda (Z.mul n n) <span class="kw">in</span></span>
<span id="cb1-15"><a href="#cb1-15" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="kw">let</span> l x = Z.div (Z.sub x Z.one) n <span class="kw">in</span></span>
<span id="cb1-16"><a href="#cb1-16" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  Z.rem (Z.mul (l cl) mu) n</span>
<span id="cb1-17"><a href="#cb1-17" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  </span>
<span id="cb1-18"><a href="#cb1-18" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">(* addition *)</span></span>
<span id="cb1-19"><a href="#cb1-19" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="kw">let</span> encrypted_add c1 c2 n =</span>
<span id="cb1-20"><a href="#cb1-20" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  Z.rem (Z.mul c1 c2) (Z.mul n n)</span></code></pre></div>
<p>The hypergraph itself is defined as follows:</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb2"><pre
class="sourceCode ocaml"><code class="sourceCode ocaml"><span id="cb2-1"><a href="#cb2-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="kw">type</span> hyperedge = { vertices: vertex <span class="dt">list</span>; weight: Z.t }</span>
<span id="cb2-2"><a href="#cb2-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="kw">type</span> hypergraph = hyperedge <span class="dt">list</span></span>
<span id="cb2-3"><a href="#cb2-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb2-4"><a href="#cb2-4" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="kw">let</span> create_hyperedge m public_key =</span>
<span id="cb2-5"><a href="#cb2-5" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  [encrypt m public_key]</span>
<span id="cb2-6"><a href="#cb2-6" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">(* literally wraps Paillier ciphertext in a list *)</span></span></code></pre></div>
<p>From Octra’s code examples, a hypergraph is now defined as a list
containing one Paillier ciphertext. Adding two hyperedges is just
standard Paillier homomorphic multiplication. How exciting, no? They get
even smaller things wrong! Let’s look at <a
href="https://docs.octra.org/tech-docs/hfhe/hfhe-key-sharding">key
sharding</a>. They give the following equations to represent their HFHE
key sharding:</p>
<pre><code>DK = BLAKE3(VC ⊕ SK ⊕ (VC × large_prime))
SK_shard_i = BLAKE3(VC_i ⊕ salt_i)
SK_final_i = BLAKE3(SK_shard_i)</code></pre>
<p>Do you see the issue? The main issue is that this is not how key
sharding (also called secret sharing) works! Typically, when we are
speaking about key sharding, we think of it maintaining three
properties. - Shards reveal zero information about the original secret
key material. - A t-of-n threshold of shards is required to fully
reconstruct the key (see <a
href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shamir&#39;s_secret_sharing">SSS</a>
and <a href="https://eprint.iacr.org/2020/852.pdf">FROST</a>) - The
reconstruction itself is mathematical, not hash-based. Octra doesn’t
seem to get that. They describe a process, instead, which is more
equivalent to the nested hashing of the secret key with salts. What’s
important to note here is that <strong>you cannot reconstruct the secret
key by any mechanism described within the documentation</strong>. You
can’t get your secret key from your shards (and, despite the
documentation technically being outdated by Octra’s standards, this is
still a nonsensical scheme. It can be outdated by a decade, it doesn’t
make it any less obvious that the person behind this key sharding scheme
was on some serious levels of <a
href="https://wikipedia.org/wiki/Salvia">salvia</a>). But, for giggles,
let’s say you can recover your secret key. Unfortunately, it’s
nonsensical. The secret key is generated like so:</p>
<pre><code>SK = Hash(XOR(SBox transform(hashed SV elements)))</code></pre>
<p>Surely you see the problem now, yes? Legitimate FHE schemes tend to
generate secret keys from discrete Gaussian distributions over
polynomial rings. There’s far more to be disgusted by in the
documentation. Lots of undefined functions to make you sick. What if we
were unfair, though? Mayhaps we misread the documentation because of our
staunch incompetence in regards to everything we do. How unfortunate! In
that case, we’d like to ask Octra themselves. <del>What is your hardness
assumption? Can you meaningfully substantiate the architecture of your
documented systems? Why do the properties of boolean operations over
hypergraphs transfer into FHE?</del></p>
<h5 id="some-time-later">Some time later…</h5>
<p>Good news, friends! We know now! They claim to utilise <a
href="https://www.cs.umd.edu/~gasarch/TOPICS/pcp/hastadopt.pdf">LPN
hardness assumptions</a> for their scheme of hypergraph-based FHE. Let’s
look at a 2026 paper by <a
href="(https://eprint.iacr.org/2026/1130)">Dunkelman et al.</a> for a
little, shall we? I know I previously asked why the properties of
boolean operations over hypergraphs transfer to FHE, however, there’s a
more glaring question here. How do LPN assumptions transfer to FHE?
Short answer: no clue! Before you get the long answer, I want to be very
clear, the paper itself speaks on LPN-C, a construction on top of LPN.
It’s not solely LPN assumptions, but–as the name suggests–it is
ubiquitously dependent on it. The paper shows that it has an effective
security 5-14 bits below the claimed levels as a result of rejection
sampling effects and that iterative attacks are an efficient threat to
secret matrices. For the long answer: Octra developed their scheme on an
entirely unproven (and actively contested) assumption, that LPN hardness
cleanly transfers over to FHE. Not only has Octra failed to provide any
legitimate evidence to suggest a suggestion of such a haughty security
reduction, <em>they still don’t even have a whitepaper</em>! They claim
to be working on it, but that doesn’t matter when your entire chain is
built on a gamble. As I said to <code>@chiefofautism</code> on X, we
intended on taking some bets. That’s why we have <a
href="https://usogui.fandom.com/wiki/Madarame_Baku">Baku Madarame</a> as
the cover image. The only difference is that they gamble with VC money.
Let’s raise, in that case. Those of you who are informed may know that
there was a <a href="https://github.com/lamafab/octra-hfhe-lean">Lean 4
+ Mathlib formalisation of HFHE</a>. There’s a few things of note here.
Firstly is that the person who made the verification,
<code>lamafab</code>, is entirely legitimate. This isn’t like Silvan who
we found out is correlated, this is a person who genuinely loves their
crypto. Secondly, the formalisation is meant to prove that HFHE is an
exact homomorphic scheme. Put simply, what you throw in and compute in
is what you would get out had you just computed on it. Additionally, the
lean formalisation allows for noise tuples to cancel exactly, meaning
(from a formalisation perspective) there is no decryption noise.
However, things such as <a
href="https://wikipedia.org/wiki/Ciphertext_indistinguishability">IND-CPA</a>
and LPN to FHE hardness are either not touched or <a
href="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/lamafab/octra-hfhe-lean/refs/heads/main/Octra/HFHE/Security.lean">kept
as an assumption</a>. Another thing that I want you to notice is that it
assumes a <a
href="https://wikipedia.org/wiki/Cryptographically_secure_pseudorandom_number_generator">CSPRNG</a>
for randomness.</p>
<p>I’ll get back to this, however, just note that the proof itself uses
such.</p>
<p>There’s also several bounty findings that confirms that this proof
was far more about algebraic correctness than actual security (such as
<a
href="https://github.com/octra-labs/pvac_hfhe_cpp/issues/75">#75</a>).
Remember when we asked what was fully-homomorphic about HFHE? Back when
we assumed the docs weren’t “hopelessly outdated”? Let’s ask that
question now. What is truly fully-homomorphic about HFHE? In fact, what
is fully-homomorphic about FHE? Put simply, <a
href="https://ringcipher.com/2014/05/24/gentrys-bootstrapping-theorem-and-patents/">FHE
is defined as Somewhat Homomorphic Encryption (SHE) with
bootstrapping</a>. Formally speaking, FHE requires unbounded evaluation
of arbitrary circuits, secure bootstrapping, and IND-CPA security. From
what it looks like, HFHE can actually be pretty helpful. It has
recryption and everything. Certainly that won’t be an won’t be an issue,
right? Enter <a href="../files/fury.sage">FURY</a>. FURY is an attack
based on self-referential key recovery we discovered during this
research. Put simply, Octra does NOT solely use LPN, rather, they sneak
in a secondary assumption. Naturally, rather than trying to make it seem
viable (such as with lattices), they use a quadratic <a
href="https://wikipedia.org/wiki/Pseudorandom_number_generator">PRF</a>.
The PRF itself is broken, which means that it cannot be used to viably
encrypt anything. This lead to FURY, which allows us to extract
<code>prf_k</code>, the PRF secret key, from <code>Rku</code>, the
public bootstrapping key using no ciphertexts (whereas a previous
version of the attack required multiple ciphertexts with known
plaintexts to function). Let’s take a quick look at the
<code>pvac_hfhe_cpp</code> repository (the same repository they urged us
to look at more, leading to this update). Namely,
<code>/include/pvac/ops/recrypt_src_core.hpp</code> at commit
<code>e2835df</code>, lines 73-76.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb5"><pre
class="sourceCode cpp"><code class="sourceCode cpp"><span id="cb5-1"><a href="#cb5-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="kw">inline</span> Fp ru_y<span class="op">(</span><span class="at">const</span> SecKey<span class="op">&amp;</span> sk<span class="op">,</span> <span class="at">const</span> RSeed<span class="op">&amp;</span> seed<span class="op">,</span> <span class="dt">size_t</span> slot<span class="op">)</span> <span class="op">{</span></span>
<span id="cb5-2"><a href="#cb5-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="kw">auto</span> a <span class="op">=</span> ru_affine<span class="op">(</span>sk<span class="op">,</span> seed<span class="op">,</span> slot<span class="op">);</span></span>
<span id="cb5-3"><a href="#cb5-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="cf">return</span> fp_add<span class="op">(</span>fp_mul<span class="op">(</span>a<span class="op">,</span> a<span class="op">),</span> fp_from_u64<span class="op">(</span><span class="dv">1</span><span class="op">));</span></span>
<span id="cb5-4"><a href="#cb5-4" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="op">}</span></span></code></pre></div>
<p>The PRF mask is computed as <code>R = (a^2 + 1)^-1</code> where
<code>a = ru_affine(sk, seed, slot)</code>. The function
<code>ru_affine</code> is at lines 65-71.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb6"><pre
class="sourceCode cpp"><code class="sourceCode cpp"><span id="cb6-1"><a href="#cb6-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="kw">inline</span> Fp ru_affine<span class="op">(</span><span class="at">const</span> SecKey<span class="op">&amp;</span> sk<span class="op">,</span> <span class="at">const</span> RSeed<span class="op">&amp;</span> seed<span class="op">,</span> <span class="dt">size_t</span> slot<span class="op">)</span> <span class="op">{</span></span>
<span id="cb6-2"><a href="#cb6-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    Fp acc <span class="op">=</span> ru_fp<span class="op">(</span>seed<span class="op">,</span> <span class="dv">0</span><span class="op">,</span> <span class="dv">0</span><span class="op">,</span> slot<span class="op">);</span></span>
<span id="cb6-3"><a href="#cb6-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="cf">for</span> <span class="op">(</span><span class="dt">size_t</span> i <span class="op">=</span> <span class="dv">0</span><span class="op">;</span> i <span class="op">&lt;</span> sk<span class="op">.</span>prf_k<span class="op">.</span>size<span class="op">();</span> <span class="op">++</span>i<span class="op">)</span> <span class="op">{</span></span>
<span id="cb6-4"><a href="#cb6-4" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>        acc <span class="op">=</span> fp_add<span class="op">(</span>acc<span class="op">,</span> fp_mul<span class="op">(</span>ru_fp<span class="op">(</span>seed<span class="op">,</span> <span class="dv">1</span><span class="op">,</span> i<span class="op">,</span> slot<span class="op">),</span> fp_from_u64<span class="op">(</span>sk<span class="op">.</span>prf_k<span class="op">[</span>i<span class="op">])));</span></span>
<span id="cb6-5"><a href="#cb6-5" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="op">}</span></span>
<span id="cb6-6"><a href="#cb6-6" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="cf">return</span> acc<span class="op">;</span></span>
<span id="cb6-7"><a href="#cb6-7" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="op">}</span></span></code></pre></div>
<p>Because you’re asking, no. I’m not “affine”. (In case you didn’t get
it, I read ru_affine as “are you fine?”). Regardless, this is linear in
the four secret elements <code>sk.prf_k[0..3]</code>. This is all to say
that we compute <code>a</code> as so:
<code>a = h_0 + k_0 h_1 + k_1 h_2 + k_2 h_3 + k_3 h_4</code>. Given
<code>h_0..h_4</code> are public from the seed via <code>ru_fp()</code>
(line 66 in <code>ru_affine()</code>), the mask is therefore a
deterministic quadratic function of four 64-bit secrets. This isn’t a
pseudorandom function nor is it a CSPRNG! This is where our initial
attack came from. Four known-plaintext ciphertexts yield four equations.
These, in turn, can be solved via Gaussian elimination. From here is
where we discover FURY. Keep the idea of “four equations” being the
threshold in mind. Let’s look at
<code>/include/pvac/ops/recrypt_ru.hpp</code>, lines 480 to 498. Pay
attention to 489-492 specifically.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb7"><pre
class="sourceCode cpp"><code class="sourceCode cpp"><span id="cb7-1"><a href="#cb7-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="kw">inline</span> Rku make_rku<span class="op">(</span><span class="at">const</span> PubKey<span class="op">&amp;</span> pk<span class="op">,</span> <span class="at">const</span> SecKey<span class="op">&amp;</span> sk<span class="op">,</span> <span class="dt">size_t</span> queries <span class="op">=</span> <span class="dv">64</span><span class="op">,</span> <span class="at">const</span> NativeRuntimeReusableBudget<span class="op">&amp;</span> budget <span class="op">=</span> NativeRuntimeReusableBudget<span class="op">{})</span> <span class="op">{</span></span>
<span id="cb7-2"><a href="#cb7-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    Rku rk<span class="op">;</span></span>
<span id="cb7-3"><a href="#cb7-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    rk<span class="op">.</span>key <span class="op">=</span> native_runtime_pubkey_digest<span class="op">(</span>pk<span class="op">);</span></span>
<span id="cb7-4"><a href="#cb7-4" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    rk<span class="op">.</span>dom <span class="op">=</span> rku_dom<span class="op">(</span>pk<span class="op">,</span> sk<span class="op">);</span></span>
<span id="cb7-5"><a href="#cb7-5" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    rk<span class="op">.</span>policy <span class="op">=</span> rk_policy<span class="op">(</span>queries<span class="op">);</span></span>
<span id="cb7-6"><a href="#cb7-6" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    rk<span class="op">.</span>budget <span class="op">=</span> budget<span class="op">;</span></span>
<span id="cb7-7"><a href="#cb7-7" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    rk<span class="op">.</span>prf <span class="op">=</span> sk<span class="op">.</span>prf_k<span class="op">.</span>size<span class="op">();</span></span>
<span id="cb7-8"><a href="#cb7-8" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    rk<span class="op">.</span>lpn <span class="op">=</span> <span class="dv">0</span><span class="op">;</span></span>
<span id="cb7-9"><a href="#cb7-9" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    rk<span class="op">.</span>sec<span class="op">.</span>reserve<span class="op">(</span>rk<span class="op">.</span>prf <span class="op">+</span> rk<span class="op">.</span>lpn<span class="op">);</span></span>
<span id="cb7-10"><a href="#cb7-10" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="cf">for</span> <span class="op">(</span><span class="dt">size_t</span> i <span class="op">=</span> <span class="dv">0</span><span class="op">;</span> i <span class="op">&lt;</span> rk<span class="op">.</span>prf<span class="op">;</span> <span class="op">++</span>i<span class="op">)</span> <span class="op">{</span></span>
<span id="cb7-11"><a href="#cb7-11" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>        <span class="kw">auto</span> seed <span class="op">=</span> rku_seed<span class="op">(</span>rk<span class="op">.</span>dom<span class="op">,</span> <span class="dv">1</span><span class="op">,</span> i<span class="op">);</span></span>
<span id="cb7-12"><a href="#cb7-12" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>        rk<span class="op">.</span>sec<span class="op">.</span>push_back<span class="op">(</span>enc_ru_value_seeded<span class="op">(</span>pk<span class="op">,</span> sk<span class="op">,</span> sk<span class="op">.</span>prf_k<span class="op">[</span>i<span class="op">],</span> seed<span class="op">.</span>data<span class="op">(),</span> <span class="dv">4</span><span class="op">));</span></span>
<span id="cb7-13"><a href="#cb7-13" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="op">}</span></span>
<span id="cb7-14"><a href="#cb7-14" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    rk<span class="op">.</span>view <span class="op">=</span> rku_view<span class="op">(</span>pk<span class="op">,</span> rk<span class="op">);</span></span>
<span id="cb7-15"><a href="#cb7-15